snippet.textDisplay:
Here's your biggest problem with repeatedly saying the revisionist history in this movie is not emotionally effective. Which is how you described the revisionist narrative before the last minute to cover your ass

If the Manson cult didn't exist the entirety of American history, specifically the hippie movement and war on drugs would've changed. The Manson family murders were considered as the end of the 60s and the end of hippie counter culture. The 70s were a more tense decade for this reason as well as the war on drugs which was partially started due to the Manson Family Murders. The fact that you said that Inglorious Basterds is more emotional because it does kill the Nazis is silly compared to a story where the key players IE the victims weren't killed. Sure you have to know about the Nazis to feel that satisfaction if them burning to death but you also need to know about the Manson family to truly understand how beautiful their loss would've been. The fact that they ended a period of counter culture based in free love by killing people in cold blood is fucked up which is the whole point of them losing and Sharon Tate getting to live.

Also your point about the narrator not working if he was in Jackie Brown is because this movie is about a fairy tale. Jackie Brown is about a realistic crime story that made the story so tense narration is unnecessary. Whereas in this film the story is a storybook style story and in those narrations the narrator is always in the beginning and end or just before the ultimate climax. Think back to when you were a kid and had an imagination. The story and its narrator is ignired after you get into the meat and comes back by the end because your mind is wrapping up the story. This is why disney often had narration at the beginning and end and not always throughout the story. The narrator often gets in the way. He is still telling the story but the action overrides the voice.

snippet.textDisplay: I understand that the movie is a love letter to Hollywood, and to films, and that it's more for avid film lovers than it is for a casual fan. That being said, the whole payoff of the movie, the big climax, kinda depends on you knowing the backstory of Sharon Tate, and the Manson family. I belong to a younger generation, and I'm not from US, so maybe that's the reason why I don't have that insight. I'm grateful that I watched it at home on blu ray, so I was able to pause it, then google stuff to connect the dots between "Charlie", the hippies and the ranch, not really sure how I'd feel watching it in the theatre, cause it just wouldn't make sense why did it have to be Tate and her friends living in that house, or who the hell Terry is.

Jeremy's reaching a bit on this one.

The opening interview was obviously much longer. It was cut down so we'd only see what was really necessary for our movie watching experience. But in the time the whole interview would have been aired.

My observation about this is that it came at least TEN YEARS prior to the events in the movie:

Rick: Five years at the top. Ten years treading water. Now race to the bottom.

So Bounty Law was off the air for ten years prior to 1969, when the movie starts.
